1 G. One member of the Senate or the House of Representatives serves as a nonvoting,
2 ex officio member and serves a 2-year term commensurate with the Legislator's term
3 of office. For a Legislature that is designated with an even number, the member must
4 be a member of the House of Representatives who represents a portion of Brunswick
5 or Topsham, appointed by the Speaker of the House; in odd-numbered Legislatures,
6 the member must be a Senator who represents Brunswick or Topsham, appointed by
7 the President of the Senate.
8 Sec. 5. 5 MRSA §13083-I, sub-§4, as amended by PL 2009, c. 641, §2, is repealed.
9 Sec. 6. 5 MRSA §13083-K, sub-§5 is enacted to read:
10 5. Uniform Environmental Covenants Act. Notwithstanding any provision of law
11 to the contrary, all property held by the authority is subject to the Uniform Environmental
12 Covenants Act.
13 Sec. 7. 38 MRSA §488, sub-§15, as amended by PL 2011, c. 551, §2, is further
14 amended by enacting at the end a new last blocked paragraph to read:
15 The provisions of this subsection do not apply to the Midcoast Regional Redevelopment
16 Authority established in Title 5, section 13083-G.
17 Sec. 8. Initial term of Legislator on Midcoast Regional Redevelopment
18 Authority. Notwithstanding the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 5, section 13083-I,
19 subsection 2, paragraph G, the Speaker of the House shall appoint to the Midcoast Regional
20 Redevelopment Authority the initial member of the Legislature who must be a member of
21 the House of Representatives who represents a portion of Brunswick or Topsham; that
22 member serves on the authority until December 2, 2026.
23 Sec. 9. Establishment of environmental covenants. No later than January 1,
24 2027, the board of trustees of the Midcoast Regional Redevelopment Authority shall enter
25 into environmental covenants pursuant to the Uniform Environmental Covenants Act for
26 all property held by the authority.
27 SUMMARY
2288 This bill makes the following changes to the Midcoast Regional Redevelopment
2299 Authority.
30 1. It amends the goals of the authority to require it to engage in environmental
31 stewardship.
32 2. It increases the membership of the board of trustees of the authority by 3 members
33 to 14 members by:
34 A. Requiring the Governor to appoint a 2nd commissioner of a department of State
35 Government;
36 B. Adding a voting member appointed by the chair of the Brunswick town council;
37 and
38 C. Adding a nonvoting member who is a Senator or Representative who represents
39 Brunswick or Topsham. The Senator and Representative serve 2-year terms,
40 commensurate with their term of office, rotating back and forth.
Page 2 - 132LR1631(01)

1 3. It removes the requirement that, for the 10 appointments made by the Governor to
2 represent local communities, at least 7 must be residents of Androscoggin County,
3 Cumberland County or Sagadahoc County and instead requires that at least 4 must be
4 residents of Brunswick or Brunswick town officials or business owners.
5 4. It repeals the inclusion of the authority under the Maine Tort Claims Act and
6 removes the exemption of the board of trustees or an employee of the authority from
7 personal liability and the requirement that the authority indemnify a trustee or employee
8 against expenses incurred in the defense of an action brought against that trustee or
9 employee due to that trustee's or employee's relationship with the authority.
10 5. It requires all property held by the authority to be subject to the Uniform
11 Environmental Covenants Act and requires the board of trustees to enter into covenants
12 under that Act no later than January 1, 2027.
13 6. It removes the exemption of the authority from the site location of development laws
14 currently granted to former military bases.
